```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <unordered_map>

using namespace std;

int main()
{
    // Open the file
    ifstream file;
    file.open("file.txt");
    if (!file)
    {
        cout << "Error opening file" << endl;
        return 1;
    }

    // Create an unordered map to store the word count
    unordered_map<string, int> wordCount;

    // Read the line from the file and split it using space as the delimiter
    string line;
    getline(file, line);
    istringstream ss(line);
    while (ss >> word)
    {
        // Check if the word exists in the map, if not, then add it with a count of 1
        if (wordCount.find(word) == wordCount.end())
        {
            wordCount[word] = 1;
        }
        else
        {
            wordCount[word]++;
        }
    }

    // Display the count of the word
    for (auto & entry : wordCount)
    {
        cout << entry.first << " occurs " << entry.second << " times." << endl;
    }

    file.close();
    return 0;
}
```

This program uses an unordered map to store the frequency of each word in the text file. The code starts by opening the text file, reading a line from it, and breaking it down using space as the delimiter. Then, it converts the line into a stringstream object, which reads the line character by character. After that, it checks if the word exists in the map, if not, it is added with a count of 1. If it does exist, it is incremented by 1 in the map. Finally, it displays the count of the word in the text file.

```
file.close();
```

This command closes the file, thus ending the program.

This is just one way to solve the problem. There are many other ways to approach this problem, including using an array, a hash table, or a list to store the frequency of the words. You can choose the approach that best suits your needs. Let me know if you have any other questions or if you need any more help with the code.

